In RenderScript, my kernels should be invoked after each other - synchronously. Since it&#39;s a pipeline and the second kernel depends on the first, it lead to faulty behaviour if it doesn&#39;t wait for the first kernel to finish.

The input and output of the first kernel do not have identical dimensions, so the output of the first kernel is set using `rsAtomicInc()`.


The basic pipeline is as such: 

- first kernel: 2 bitmaps as input, 1D int array as output
- second kernel: 1D int array as output, 1D float array as input


Kotlin:
```
nextBitmapAlloc.copyFrom(nextBitmap)
previousBitmapAlloc.copyFrom(previousBitmap)

script.forEach_resetUintArray(horizontalShiftAlloc)

script.forEach_calculateVerticalShift(nextBitmapAlloc)
// Should wait for kernel to finish
script.forEach_normalizeVerticalShift(verticalShiftAlloc, verticalShiftFloatAlloc)

script.invoke_findMax()
val result = IntArray(1).apply { resultAlloc.copyTo(this) }
```

RenderScript
```
rs_allocation previousBitmap;

// Results
uint* verticalShiftArray;
float* verticalShiftFloatArray;

uint RS_KERNEL resetUintArray() {
    return 0;
}

void RS_KERNEL calculateVerticalShift(uchar4 currentInput, uint x, uint y) {
    uint shift;
    uint previousY;

    uchar4 previousInput = rsGetElementAt_uchar4(previousBitmap, x, previousY);

    if (someComparisonLogic(previousInput, currentInput)) {
        rsAtomicInc(&amp;verticalShiftArray[shift + height]);
    }
}

float RS_KERNEL normalizeHorizontalShift(uint input, uint x) {
    uint divider = divider();
    return (float) input / (float) divider;
}

void findMax() {
    float maxValue = mimumMatchRatioThreshold;
    int maxI = -1;

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; max; i++) {
        float value = verticalShiftArray[i];
        if (value &gt; maxValue) {
            maxValue = value;
            maxI = i;
        }
    }

    rsSetElementAt_int(result, maxI, 0);
}
```


The complete pipeline is called as often as possible. Sometimes, `result[0]` shows the previous result. When these lines are called again, the correct result is returned:
```
script.forEach_normalizeVerticalShift(verticalShiftAlloc, verticalShiftFloatAlloc)

script.invoke_findMax()
val result = IntArray(1).apply { resultAlloc.copyTo(this) }
```

So for some reason, the result of function `forEach_calculateVerticalShift` which should be in allocation `verticalShiftAlloc` is not ready yet. Calling `renderscript.finish` and/or `dummyIntArray.apply { verticalShiftAlloc.copyTo(this) }` between the first and second kernel helps often, but not always. It doesn&#39;t seem more accurate than bluntly using `System.sleep()` in between.

Coping `verticalShiftAlloc` and investigate it does not help; it always shows the up to date data, even when `val result` shows the previous result.

How can I wait for the `forEach_calculateVerticalShift` to be finished, so `verticalShiftAlloc` contains the latest results?

Remarks

1. For readability, I removed what seemed to me unimportant lines of code and replaced it with mock constants and functions. If this was done too rigorously, I can add more. 
2. I checked out https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21358689/renderscript-blocking-function-invokation and https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22158853/renderscript-rs-finish-allocation-syncall-copyto-wait-till-kernel-exec, but this did not help me yet.

